how would i make it so i get a single string as a return from this vector and it is always randomized which one it is 
std::vector<std::string> combos = {
    knightsForm, guardiansForm, templarsForm,
    dualBlades, shieldWall, cavalryCharge,
    lancersStrike, pikeFormation,
    mountedGuard, cavalryStrike, warriorsDefense,
    bladeMastery, fortress, stampede,
    bladeStorm, fortifiedPosition, mountedSquadron,
    phalanx, knightsCharge, mountedDefense,
    battleFormation, royalGuard, swordLegion,
    shieldLegion, cavalryLegion, grandAssault,
    grandDefense, grandCavalry, battleWall,
    perfectStrike, royalFormation, castleDefense,
    warParty
};

To get a random string from this vector, you can use C++'s random number facilities. Here's how you can do it:

```cpp
std::string getRandomCombo(const std::vector<std::string>& combos) {
    // Create a random device
    std::random_device rd;
    // Create a random number generator
    std::mt19937 gen(rd());
    // Create a distribution for the vector's size
    std::uniform_int_distribution<> dis(0, combos.size() - 1);

    // Return a random element from the vector
    return combos[dis(gen)];
}
```

You would use it like this:
```cpp
std::string randomCombo = getRandomCombo(combos);
```

Alternatively, if you want a simpler (but less random) approach, you could use:
```cpp
std::string getRandomCombo(const std::vector<std::string>& combos) {
    return combos[rand() % combos.size()];
}
```

But make sure to seed the random number generator once at the start of your program with:
```cpp
srand(time(nullptr));
```

The first approach using `std::random_device` and `std::mt19937` is generally recommended as it provides better randomization, but both approaches will work for basic randomization needs.
